    "last_edit_date" : 1481841219,
    "creation_date" : 1229078574,
    "answer_id" : 362443,
    "question_id" : 362424,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>From the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.9.5.1\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Java Language Specification</a>, section 15.9.5.1:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>An anonymous class cannot have an\n  explicitly declared constructor.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Sorry :(</p>\n\n<p>EDIT: As an alternative, you can create some final local variables, and/or include an instance initializer in the anonymous class. For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Test {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        final int fakeConstructorArg = 10;\n\n        Object a = new Object() {\n            {\n                System.out.println(\"arg = \" + fakeConstructorArg);\n            }\n        };\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>It's grotty, but it might just help you. Alternatively, use a proper nested class :)</p>\n"
  }, {
