    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here's another way around the problem:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Test{\n\n    public static final void main(String...args){\n\n        new Thread(){\n\n            private String message = null;\n\n            Thread initialise(String message){\n\n                this.message = message;\n                return this;\n            }\n\n            public void run(){\n                System.out.println(message);\n            }\n        }.initialise(args[0]).start();\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1463702,
      "reputation" : 11,
      "user_id" : 1377250,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cad9e9500a8503443d6edc55e5f1030?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "arnaldocan",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1377250/arnaldocan"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1354839610,
    "last_edit_date" : 1354839610,
    "creation_date" : 1336245274,
    "answer_id" : 10465155,
    "question_id" : 362424,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In my case, a local class (with custom constructor) worked as an anonymous class:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Object a = getClass1(x);\n\npublic Class1 getClass1(int x) {\n  class Class2 implements Class1 {\n    void someNewMethod(){\n    }\n    public Class2(int a){\n      super();\n      System.out.println(a);\n    }\n  }\n  Class1 c = new Class2(x);\n  return c;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
