    "last_activity_date" : 1631469685,
    "last_edit_date" : 1631469685,
    "creation_date" : 1442921758,
    "answer_id" : 32715815,
    "question_id" : 362424,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I know the thread is too old to post an answer. But still i think it is worth it.</p>\n<p>Though you can't have an explicit constructor, if your intention is to call a, possibly protected, constructor of the super class, then the following is all you have to do.</p>\n<pre><code>StoredProcedure sp = new StoredProcedure(datasource, spName) {\n    {// init code if there are any}\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>This is an example of creating a <a href=\"http://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/jdbc/object/StoredProcedure.html#StoredProcedure-javax.sql.DataSource-java.lang.String-\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><strong><code>StoredProcedure</code></strong></a> object in Spring by passing a <code>DataSource</code> and a <code>String</code> object.</p>\n<p>So the Bottom line is, if you want to create an anonymous class and want to call the super class constructor then create the anonymous class with a <strong>signature matching the super class constructor</strong>.</p>\n"
  } ],
